{{出典の明記|date=2017th year 8月28日 (月) 07:45 (UTC)}} {{afc comment|1=I think Stupa might fit better than Pagoda due to being one level tall but not sure[[User:Immanuelle|Immanuelle]] ([[User talk:Immanuelle|talk]]) 23:39, 6 April 2025 (UTC)}} {{Japanese Imperial Rituals}} {{nihongo|'''{{subst:PAGNEAME}}'''|宝塔|hōtō}} has the following two meanings: * It is one architectural style of Buddhist pagodas, referring to a single-storied tower with a cylindrical body. (This article explains this meaning.) * It is also an honorific term for Buddhist pagodas in general. ---- == Form and Significance of the Pagoda == A ''pagoda'' (宝塔, hōtō) is one architectural style of Buddhist pagodas. Although the term “pagoda” is sometimes used honorifically to refer to pagodas in general regardless of form or style, in the terminology of Japanese architectural history it refers specifically to a single-storied pagoda having a cylindrical core (tower body) topped with a flat, square roof<ref>{{Cite book|title=日本石造美術辞典|last=川勝|first=政太郎|date=1978|publisher=東京堂|page=347}}; {{Cite book|title=古建築の基礎知識|last=前久夫|date=1986|publisher=光村推古書院|page=61}}</ref>. The upper portion of the cylinder is rounded off in a style known as “kame-bara” (turtle-belly). A row of ornamental rings (相輪) similar to those on multi-storied pagodas is placed on top of the roof. Pagodas may be constructed of wood, metal, or stone, although extant examples of wooden pagodas are extremely rare. In Japan, the oldest surviving example of a wooden pagoda is a bronze pagoda from the Ikegami Honmon-ji complex (built around the first year of the Hōan era, late Heian period)<ref>{{Cite book|title=日本石造美術辞典|last=川勝|first=政太郎|date=1978|publisher=東京堂|page=347}}</ref>. Note that a two-storied structure in which a flat, circular upper story is mounted on top of an initial flat, square story (known as a “Tahōtō”) is distinguished from the pagoda described here; this distinction is merely conventional.
