=== Indoor Mini-Pagodas === * {{ill|Jikō-ji (Tokigawamachi, Saitama)|ja|慈光寺|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Saitama Prefecture, Important Cultural Property) – built in 1556 (Tenmon 25). * {{ill|Seikai-ji (Ina City)|ja|性海寺|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Aichi Prefecture, Important Cultural Property) * {{ill|Chōzō-ji (Minō City)|ja|長蔵寺|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Gifu Prefecture, Important Cultural Property) * Honmon-ji (in Tokyo, Important Cultural Property) – built in 1830 (Bunsei 13); this pagoda is contained within the Honmon-ji complex.
=== Stone Pagodas === Stone pagodas occupy a major section of the field of [[Stone Art]]. Some stone pagodas feature carved door-like panels or images of two figures (the Manyo Rulai and Shakyamuni) on the cylindrical body. Regional examples include the {{ill|Kunō-tō|ja|国東塔|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Kunisaki, Ōita|ja|国東|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Ōita Prefecture, and the {{ill|Akazaki-tō|ja|赤碕塔|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Tottori Prefecture|ja|鳥取県|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. * {{ill|Kurama-dera|ja|鞍馬寺|qq=draft|qq=draft}} Stone Pagoda (in Kyoto, National Treasure) – an inscribed Buddhist scripture tube bearing the inscription of the Hōan era (【1120】) was discovered buried in the soil beneath the tower. It is considered the oldest extant example of a stone pagoda. * Ruins of {{ill|Kande-ji|ja|関寺|qq=draft|qq=draft}}: “Ushi-tō” (Stone Pagoda), (in Shiga Prefecture, Important Cultural Property) – from the late Heian period; 3.3 m tall with an octagonal roof; the ornamental ring atop the roof was added later. It, together with the Kurama-dera pagoda, Ranks among the oldest. * The ruins of the pagoda at {{ill|Mangan-ji|ja|満願寺|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (in Takashima City, Shiga Prefecture) – from the early Kamakura period; 4 m tall; the ornamental ring was added later. * {{ill|Jōdo-ji (Onomichi)|ja|浄土寺|qq=draft|qq=draft}} Pagoda (in Onomichi, Hiroshima Prefecture, Important Cultural Property) – inscribed with the date of the first year of the Kōan era (【1278】); 2.8 m tall; built using rammed earth on a dais. * {{ill|Saimei-ji (Kōra-cho, Shiga)|ja|西明寺|qq=draft|qq=draft}} Pagoda (in Kōra-cho, Shiga Prefecture, Important Cultural Property) – inscribed with the 2nd year of the Jiagen era (【1304】). * {{ill|Ishiyama-dera|ja|石山寺|qq=draft|qq=draft}} Stone Pagoda (in Ōtsu, Shiga Prefecture) – from the mid-Kamakura period; currently about 2 m tall, though originally estimated at about 3 m. * Ishiyama-dera “Mekakushi-iwa” (in Shiga Prefecture) – from the Heian period. * {{ill|Anyō-ji (Higashiyama, Kyoto)|ja|安養寺|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (with a pagoda attributed to {{ill|Jien|ja|慈円|qq=draft|qq=draft}}) (in Kyoto, Important Cultural Property) – from the mid-Kamakura period; approximately 3 m tall with carvings of the Manyo and Shakyamuni Buddhas on the tower body. * {{ill|Roppōmitsu-ji|ja|六波羅蜜寺|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Agoya-tsuka (in Kyoto Prefecture) – from the Kamakura period. * {{ill|Chōraku-ji (Ota City)|ja|長楽寺|qq=draft|qq=draft}} Pagoda (in Ota City, Gunma Prefecture, Important Cultural Property) – built in the 2nd year of Kenchi (【1276】).
== References == * Ishida Shigesaku, “Pagoda – Tower and Tower-Ba (Stūba)”, Japanese Art 77, 1972, Shibundo. * Nakani Tō, “Overview of Japanese Pagodas”, 1970, Bunka-dō. * Kawakatsu Masatarō, “Introduction to Stone Art”, 1967, Shakai Shisōsha.
